This is where the actions happen.

60
05:54:00,000 --> 06:00:00,000

61
06:00:00,000 --> 06:06:00,000
Step one. Calculate and display cost estimate.
This is a debug log action that prints an ASCII table to the console.

62
06:06:00,000 --> 06:12:00,000
The table shows compute cost based on traffic tier.
Low traffic. CPU twelve dollars. Memory eight dollars. Spot capacity type.
Seventy percent discount.

63
06:12:00,000 --> 06:18:00,000
Medium traffic. CPU twenty-eight dollars. Memory eighteen dollars.
On-Demand capacity type.

64
06:18:00,000 --> 06:24:00,000
High traffic. CPU ninety-five dollars. Memory fifty-two dollars.
HPA with one to ten replicas.

65
06:24:00,000 --> 06:30:00,000
If database is needed, RDS t4g.micro PostgreSQL costs sixteen dollars per month.
Stop and start schedule reduces effective cost to about six dollars per month.

66
06:30:00,000 --> 06:36:00,000
If cache is needed, ElastiCache t4g.micro Redis costs twelve dollars per month.
If S3 is needed, storage with lifecycle policy costs about five dollars per month.

67
06:36:00,000 --> 06:42:00,000
Platform costs for ECR, CloudWatch, and NAT total about eight dollars per month.
Total estimate for low traffic is thirty-three to forty-five dollars per month.
Medium traffic is sixty to eighty dollars per month.
High traffic is one hundred sixty to two hundred twenty dollars per month.

68
06:42:00,000 --> 06:48:00,000
The table also lists optimizations applied automatically.
Spot instances for low-traffic workloads.
Graviton ARM64 instances where available.
Gp3 storage on all EBS volumes.
S3 lifecycle policy if S3 selected.
RDS stop and start schedule if database selected.
ECR lifecycle policy on container repository.

